THE PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING WHILE UNLOADING IN BELLY #31 OF FLIGHT 2915-AIRCRAFT #703 FROM ONTARIO. THE LEAKING PARCEL WAS MARKED ORM-B. A MERCURY SPILL WAS ALSO DISCOVERED IN THE AIRCRAFT. THE PACKAGE WAS THEN INSPECTEDFOR INTERNAL PROBLEMS. ONE OF FIVE,  2.268 KG BOTTLES HAD A LOOSE CAP. THE CAP WAS TIGHTENED AND THE COMPLETE PACKAGE WAS REPACKED ACCORDING TO NSTA 1-A STANDARDS AND SHIPPED BY GROUND SERVICE TO THE CONSIGNEE, PER SHIPPERS REQUEST. SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED BY IOWA CUSTOMER SERVICE AND REVIEWED DISCREPANCIES LEADING TO THE INCIDENT, AND CORRECTIVE MEASURES TO BE TAKEN. AN INCORRECT SHIPPING PRACTIVE CARD AND A COPY OF THIS REPORT WAS SENT TO THE ORIGIN DISTRICT FOR CUSTOMER FOLLOW-UP.

OUR DRIVER ARRIVED AT DESTINATION AND HE AND THE RECEIVER STARTED TO REMOVE THE BLANK FLANGE ON THE END OF THE TRANSFER HOSE.  AS THEY LOSSENED THE BOLTS THEY HEARD A HISS OF PRESSURE.  THIS PROMPTLY STOPPED AND THE FIRST BOLT WAS REMOVED COMPLETELY.  AS THEY STARTED TO LOOSEN THE SECOND BOLT PRODUCT STARTED SPURTING FROM THE HOSE.  THEY OBTAINED A BUCKET TO CATCH THE MATERIAL BUT APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS SPILLED ONTO THE CONCRETE PAD ADN WAS DIKED, TREATED WITH SODA ASH AND PLACED IN CONTAINERS FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.  THE DELIVERY WAS THEN COMPLETED WITHOUT FURTHER DIFFICULTY.  IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE SHIPPER, AFTER LOADING THE TRAILER, PRESSURE TESTS IT TO MAKE SURE THE VESSEL IS SECURE.  EVIDENTLY THE PRODUCT VALVE WAS NOT SECURELY CLOSED AND SOM PRODUCT WAS FORCED INTO THE UNLOADING LINE.

DOCKMAN FORKED DRUM WHILE UNLOADING. THE DRUM WAS TIPPED ON ITS SIDE TO PREVENT FURTHER LEAKING. THE SPILL WAS TAKEN UP WITH OIL DRY. THE DRUM WAS IMMEDIATELY PLACED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER FOR PROPER DISPOSAL. DOT #'S NOT AVAILABLE DUE TO PLACING IN SALVAGE DRUM.

column168: WHILE EXITING FROM INTERSTATE, DRIVER APPLIED BRAKES TOO HARD RESULTING IN A LOAD SHIFT. REPRESENTATIVES FROM THE SHIPPER AND CARRIER WERE SENT TO INVESTIGATE FOR POSSIBLE LEAKAGE. THE DOORS WERE OPENED REVEALING THE PRESENCE OF FUMES. THE SHIPPER'S VERBAL REPORT COMMUNICATED THAT SOME OF THE DRUMS SLID TOGETHER IN SUCH A WAY THAT THE RETAINING RING ON ONE DRUM WAS UNDER THE ADJACENT DRUM AND BEARING INTO THE SOFT METAL SIDEWALL. NO REFERENCE WAS MADE TO LEAKAGE. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE LOAD COULD BE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER 30 MILES DISTANT, WITHOUT THE DANGER OF LEAKAGE. THE DRIVER WAS INSTRUCTED TO DRIVE BACK TO SHIPPER WHILE THE CARRIER REPRESENTATIVE FOLLOWED CLOSELY BEHIND, CONTINUALLY MONITORING FOR EVIDENCE OF LEAKAGE. AFTER THE LOAD REACHED THE SHIPPER WITH NO INDICATIONS OF ANY HAZARDOUS MATERIALS LEAK, THE REPRESENTATIVE OF THE CARRIER TERMINATED HIS ASSIGNMENT.  THE SHIPPER OFFLOADED ALL DRUMS FOR INSPECTION.  THE TRAILER WAS RELEASED.  UPON RECEIPT OF THE ADJUSTER'S REPORT, AND SUBSEQUENT INSPECTION OF CORRESPONDING PHOTOS, IT WAS FOUND THAT A FEW SMALL DROPS HAD LEAKED ONTO THE DECK OF THE TRAILER. CONSEQUENTLY, THIS REPORT IS SUBMITTED TO SATISFY ALL REPORTING REQUIREMENTS.

column168: DOCK MAN WAS UNLOADING TRAILER WHEN HE DISCOVERED THE DAMAGED CARTON IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER. A SKID OF FREIGHT HAD BEEN PUSHED UP AGAINST THE CARTON CAUSING THE METAL CANS INSIDE TO BUCKLE AND LEAK. FREIGHT WAS TRANSFERRED TO OS &D WHERE THE CONTENTS WERE RECOUPED INTO 2-5 GAL PAILS AND FORWARDED TO ITS DESTINATION. DOCKMEN SHOULD BE MORE CAREFUL WHEN LOADING SKIDDED FREIGHT SO IT WON'T DAMAGE OTHER CARTONS ALREADY LOADED ON A TRAILER.
OTHER FREIGHT LOADED ON TOP OF (2) PAILS CAUSED A SMAL PUNCTURE IN BOTH PAILS. BOTH PAILS AND ASSOCIATED DEBRIS PLACED IN A RECOVERY DRUM PENDING DISPOSITION.

THE LEAKING SHIPMENT WAS LOCATED IN A KEYPAD AREA IN THE SORT CENTER. UPON APPROACHING THE AREA, INITIAL INSPECTION REVEALED THAT A FIBERBOARD BOX WAS SATURATED  ON ONE SIDE. THIS SHIPMENT WAS LABELED CORROSIVE. A PH TEST WAS DONE ON THE WET AREA AND GOT A PH READING OF 0. THE SHIPMENT CONTAINED 2 1 GALLON PLASTIC CONTAINERS LEAKING A CLEAR FLUID THAT ALSO PH TESTED 0. THE CAPS ON THE PLASTIC JUGS WERE LOOSENED AND THIS IS WHERE THE LEAKING OCCURED. DUE TO THE PAKAGE LABEL AND MARKINGS, PH TEST, AND THE FACT THAT 1 EMPLOYEE CAME IN CONTACT WITH THE LIQUID. THIS SHIPMENT WAS HELD AND A MSDS WAS REQUESTED.  THE MSDS STATED THAT THE LIQUID WAS COMPOUND CLEANING LIQUID.  UNDER 49 CFR COMPUND CLEANING LIQUID IS A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CLASSIFIED AS CORROSIVE. THIS SHIPMENT WAS HELD UNDER LOCK AND KEY IN THE WILMINGTON HAZMAT SECURITY CAGE FOR FAA INVESTIGATION.

DRIVER WAS TRANSFERRING PRODUCT FROM TRAILER INTO TRUCK VIA TRUCK CARGO PUMP. WHEN THE PUMP ENGAGED, THE VALVE AT THE TRUCK TANK WAS NOT OPEN, CAUSING THE SEALING GASKET BETWEEN THE VALVE AND HOSE CONNECTION TO FALL UNDER PRESSURE. DRIVER IMMEDIATELY STOPPED PUMPING, SECURED ALL HOSES AND STARTED CLEAN UP OPERATIONS. AS SOON AS THIS WAS SECURED, DRIVER CONTACTED MANAGEMENT FOR INSTRUCTIONS. I. T. CORP OF MARTINEZ WAS CALLED IN FOR SITE CLEAN-UP. DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON OFF LOADING PROCEDURES AND PRODUCT TRANSFER SAFETY.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: DRIVER ARRIVED AT SITE TO DELIVER GASOLINE FOR A TANK TEST (TIGHTNESS). TESTING PERSONNEL HAD REMOVED VAPOR RECOVERY VENTS AND TANK VENTS WERE CAPPED. TEST PERSONNEL ASKED DRIVER TO FILL TANK REGARDLESS. DRIVER USED A 3" DOWNSPOUT WITH A SEALING GLAND. 5 TO 7 MINUTES INTO THE UNLOADING, PRESSURE BUILT UP IN THE TANK, BLOWING GASOLINE BACK OUT AROUND THE SEALING GLAND. DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CEASED PRODUCT FLOW, BUT TANK CONTINUED TO BLOW GAS FROM THE FILL STEM. CLEANUP WAS INITIATED USING ABSORBENT PADS AND GEL.  DRIVER STATES THAT IT WAS A SUNNY AY WITH A LIGHT WIND BLOWING, AND FELT THAT MOST OF THE SPILLED PRODUCT WOULD EVAPORATE.  HE ALSO SAID THAT HE HAD MOPPED UP ALL FREE STANDING LIQUID.  HE WAS RELEASED FROM THE SITE BY TESTING PERSONNEL AND RETURNED TO THE MARTINEZ YARD TO REPORT THE SPILL.  UNDER THE CIRCUMSTANCES, WE BELIEVE THAT THE DRIVER DID ALL HE WAS SUPPOSED TO DO AS FAR AS CLEANUP.

CAUSE OF INCIDENT WAS DUE TO THE PHYSICAL WARMING OF THE TEFLON-TYPE GASKET SEAL ON THE INSIDE OF THE TOP DOMES. THIS ALLLOWED THEM TO BECOME SOFT AND LOSE THEIR TIGHT SEAL. APPROX 5 GALLONS OF F003 LISTED WASTE WAS SPILT ON TO THE ROADWAY SURFACE. DRIVER NOTICED A SOLVENT SMELL AND INVESTIGATED.  HE ASCERTAINED THE LIQUID SUBSTANCE ON THE ROAD SURFACE WAS COMING FROM HIS TRAILER.  HE IMMEDIATELY SECURED THE SPILL WITH OIL DRY AND SPILL PADS AND CALLED THE OFFICE FOR FURTHER ASSISTANCE. A NINE-MAN CREW WAS DISPATCHED WITH MORE ABOSRBEBT MATERIALS.  THESE WERE APPLIED TO THE ROADWAY, SWEPT UP AND PLACED INTO TWO 17-H DRUMS WHICH WERE RETURNED TO DELAWARE CONTAINER COMPANY, INC.; A FACILITY FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.  A SECOND TRUCK WAS SENT TO VACUUM OFF APPROX 1000 GALLONS OF THE MATERIAL AND BOTH TRUCKS RETURNED TO THE DELAWARE CONTAINER FACILITY. BEFORE RETURNING TO SERVICE, THE GARAGE CHECKED ALL DOMES INCLUDING THE GASKET SEALS, VALVES AND CAPS.  IN THE FUTURE, DRIVERS WILL BE INSTRUCTED TO LOAD HEATED LOADS, TIGHTEN DOWN ALL HOLD-DOWN CLAMPS, AND THEN ALLOW THE TEMPERATURE WITHIN THE TANK TO STABILIZE IN AOUT 15 MIN.  THEN THE DRIVER WILL BE INSTRUCTED TO RECHECK ALL HOLD-DOWN CLAMPS BEFORE PROCEEDING WITH THE TRANSPORT OF THE LOAD.  LAST VISUAL INSPECTION WAS DONE ON THE UNIT ON 2/8/90.

ON MARCH 21, 190 AT APPROXIMATELY 5:50 PM. OUR DRIVER BUTCH HOUSE WAS PULLED OVER IN CLYDE OHIO BECAUSE OF A LEAKING TRAILER.  THE TRAILER WAS CARRYING MATERIAL CLASSIFIED AS HYDROCHLORIC WASTE, SPENT PICKLE LIQUOR, UN 1789 PICKED UP AT AMERICAN SPRING WIRE FOR DELIVERY TO VICKERY, OHIO. LEADAGE OF THE TRAILER'S CONTENTS WERE IDENTIFIED IN FOUR DIFFERENT AREAS:,  1. ROUTE 20 IN CLYDE, OHIO.  2. CORNER OF ROUTE 113 AND ROUTE 20 IN BELLEVUE.  3. AREA BETWEEN ROUTE 250 AND 113 AND FOR EXIT 7 OF THE OHIO TURNPIKE.  AFTER BEING PULLED OVER, BUTCH HOUSE INSERTED HIS SPARE RUPTURE DISK FROM HIS SPILL KIT TO PREVENT FURTHER LEAKAGE ON HIS WAY TO VICKERY. IT WAS DECIDED THAT VICKERY WOULD PROCEED WITH CLEAN UP OPERATIONS AND NOTIFYING THE PROPER AUTHORITIES.  PUBLIC UTILITY COMPANY OF OHIO (PUCO) AND NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER (NRC) AND OHIO EPA WERE NOTIFIED.  A CLEAN UP CREW RESPONDED TO EACH SPILL AREA DURING THE NIGHT AND AT EACH SITE THEY SPREAD LIME OVER THE SPILL AN THEN SHOVELED UP THE MATERIAL INTO POLY DRUMS.  THE PH OF THE MATERIAL WAS CHECKED EACH TIME BEFORE IT WAS DRUMMED TO ENSURE IT WAS NEUTRAL.  PUCO SAID THEY WOULD INSPECT THE TRAILER ON MARCH 22.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT APPROXIMATE 53 GALLONS OF THE LOAD HAD LEAKED OUT.

column168: DRIVER WAS PROCEEDING SOUTHBOUND ON I 295 JUST INSIDE PORTLAND CITY LIMITS WHEN SHE RAN OFF ROAD TO RIGHT ON A LEFT CURVE. SHE HIT A GUARDRAIL ON RIGHT AND EVENTUALLY ROLLED THE VEHICLE ON TO ITS RIGHT SIDE, AFTER TEARING DOWN MUCH OF THE GUARDRAIL AND TREES.  PARTIALLY ON SHOULDER AND IN TRAVEL LANE OF ROADWAY. THE RUPTURE DISK AND A PART OF SPILL DAM WERE DAMAGED IN ACCIDENT SO AS TO CAUSE RELEASE OF LIQUID PRODUCT. THE PRODUCT THAT WAS SPILLED AND RECOVERED WAS CONTAMINATED AND AMOUNTED TO ADOUT 1400 GALLONS. THE ROADWAY WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH SODA ASH AND THE EMBANKMENT WAS FURTHER NEUTRALIZED WITH HYDRATED LIME AND FLUSHED FOR 5 DAYS WITH COMPANY CREWS. THE CONTAMINATED PRODUCT RECOVERED WAS DISPOSED OF BY CLEAN HARBORS OF SOUTH PORTLAND, MAINE. THE SITE IS NEUTRALIZED AND HAS BEEN ACCEPTED BY STATE EPA. THE REMAINING PRODUCT IN THE TANK WAS STILL VIRGIN PRODUCT AND WAS RETURNED TO LCP CHEMICALS-ORRINGTON, MAINE, FOR RE-PROCESSING AFTER BEING TRANSFERRED AT THE SCENE INTO ONE OF OUR TANKS. APPROXIMATELY 1500 GALLONS WERE UNRECOVERED AND WERE NEUTRALIZED BEING TAKEN OUT TO SEA BY THE TIDE.

THE BOX FELL FROM THE FORKLIFT, WHICH RAN OVER IT, CAUSING THE BOX AND CAN TO DISINTERGRATE. THE LIQUID RELEASED WAS SMOTHERED WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM. THE BOX WAS NOT MARKED AND LABELLED WITH DANGEROUS GOODS INFORMATION, NOR WAS THERE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS PRESENT, BUT DOCUMENTS WITHIN IDENTIFIED THE CONTNETS AS A DOT HAZARDOUS COMBUSTIBLE LIQUID, NOS, NA1993. NEITHER OUTER NOR INNER CONTAINER IS DOT SPEC. FORKLIFT DRIVERS HAVE BEEN ADVISED TO DETERMINE THE STABILITY OF THEIR PALLET LOADS BEFORE MOVING THEM.

column168: THE 1985 CHEVROLET S-10 BLAZER WAS TRAVELING NORTH ON GREERS CHAPEL RD. AT THE INTERSERSECTION OF GREERS CHAPEL ROAD WITH ERNEST BARRETT PARKWAY THE BLAZER DISREGARDED THE STOP SIGN AND PROCEEDED INTO THE INTERSECTION WITHOUT SLOWING DOWN. THE BLAZER IMPACTED THE TANK TRAILER OF AN 18 WHEEL TRUCK TRACTOR TRAILER COMBINATION AMIDSHIPS THAT WAS TRAVELING IN A WESTERLY DIRECTION ON BARRET PARKWAY. THE TANKER, A TEXACO OIL COMPANY TRUCK LOADED WITH GASOLINE, VEERED TO THE RIGHT OUT OF CONTROL AFTER DISENGAGING THE BLAZER. THE TANKER EXITED THE NORTHERN ROAD EDGE AND TRAVELLED UP A GRADUAL EMBANKMENT UNTIL COMING TO A CONTROLLED REST. AFTER STOPPING, THE TANKER'S LIQUID LOAD WAS AT SUCH AN ANGLE THAT WEIGHT SHIFT WAS INEVITABLE. THE TANKER ROLLED 3/4 OF A REVOLUTION COMING TO AN UNCONTROLLED FINAL REST ON ITS RIGHT SIDE ON BARRETT PARKWAY. AFTER IMPACT, THE BLAZER CAME TO A FINAL UNCONTROLLED REST IN THE CENTER THROUGH WESTBOUND TRAFFIC LANE OF BARRETT PARKWAY FACING IN A EASTERLY DIRECTION.

column168: THE CARGO TANK WAS CARRYING 6,50 GALLON OF VYNYL ACETATE WHICH IGNITED AS A RESULT OF THE TANK OVERTURNING.  SOME OF THE PRODUCT DID FLOW DOWN INTO SURROUNDING WATER BASIN, THE EXACT AMOUNT IS UNKNOWN.  THE MAJORITY OF THE PRODUCT WAS BURNED OFF DURING THE FIRE ACCORDING TO THE OFFICIALS OF THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RESPONSE UNIT OF THE NEW JERSEY TURNPIKE AUTHORITY AND THE NEWARK FIRE DEPT.  WATER BASIN MONITORING WAS PERFORMED IN OUTLYING AREAS BY THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS UNIT OF THE TURNPIKE AUTHORITY AND BY THE N.J. D.E.P. EMERGENCY RESPONSE UNIT.  WHEN THE ACCIDENT SCENE WAS CLEARED UP AND AL DEBRIS REMOVED, WATER MONITORING RESULTS WERE NEGATIVE OF ANY CONCENTRATED AREA OR HOT SPOTS, THIS ALSO INCLUDED LAND, AND SOIL.  DRIVER WAS TAKEN TO HOSPITAL, TREATED AND RELEASED THE FOLLOWING DAY.  POLICE REPORT AND WITNESSES SAY THE DRIVER WAS NOT SPEEDING, OUR INVESTIGATION DID NOT FIND ANY MECHANICAL DEFECTS.  THE CAUSE OF THE ACCIDENT IS STILL BEING INVESTIGATED.

column168: ON MARCH 28, LIZ SHELTON WAS UNLOADING TRAILER #280229. SHE DISCOVERED A BLACK TAR-LIKE SUBSTANCE ON SOME OF THE PACKAGES AS WELL AS ON THE BOTTOM OF THE TRAILER. LIZ ACCIDENTALLY GOT SOME OF THE SUBSTANCE ON HER ARM. WITHIN A FEW MINUTES, A PAINFUL RASH DEVELOPED AND SHE WAS TAKEN TO THE COMPANY DOCTOR. SHE WAS DIAGNOSED WITH CHEMICAL DERMATITIS AND RETURNED IMMEDIATELY TO WORK. NO OTHER SYMPTOMS HAS DEVELOPED. THE PACKAGES WITH THE SUBSTANCE WAS COVERED WITH SODIUM BICARBONATE, REPACKAGED AND THE EMPTY CARTONS CONTAINERISED INSIDE THE TRAILER. AT THIS POINT NO DETERMINATION HAS BEEN MADE AS TO EXACTLY WHAT THE SUBSTANCE IS. THE TRAILER HAS BEEN REMOVED FROM SERVICE UNTIL WE CAN DETERMINE THE EXACT SUBSTANCE INVOLVED.

column168: TRAILER 415-8146 WAS OPENED AT APPROXIMATELY 07:00, 3-27-90, AND DOCKMAN AT THAT TIME NOTICED A VERY BAD ODOR. HE REPORTED THIS TO HIS SUPERVISOR, MSDS AND EMERGENCY RESPONSE GUIDE WAS CONSULTED AND THE DECISION WAS MADE NOT TO ENTER TRAILER. AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM WAS CALLED IN FROM ST PAUL AND THE SHIPMENT WAS EXAMINED. THE TEAM SAID THAT THE CLOSURE ON ONE OF THE TOTES HAS NOT BEEN CLOSED AND THAT FUMES AND APPROXIMATELY 1/2 PINT OF MATERIAL HAD POOLED ON TOP OF THE TOTE. THIS WAS SQUEEGEED BACK INTO THE TOTE AND ANY EXCESS BLOTTED AND REMOVED BY THEM. TRAILER WAS ALLOWED TO AIR OUT FOR APPROXIMATELY 18 HOURS BEFORE THE OFFENDING TOTES AND ALL OTHER FREIGHT WAS UNLOADED WITHOUT INCIDENT. THE SHIPPER WILL BE CONTACTED AND OUR ORIGIN TERMINAL WILL BE MADE AWARE OF THIS INCIDENT IN ORDER THAT THIS MAY NOT OCCUR AGAIN.

column168: AN EMPLOYEE WAS TRANSFERRING 50% CAUSTIC FROM A RAILCAR LOCATED ON OUR SIDING TO OUT 10,000 GALLON STORAGE TANK.  THE FITTING ON OUR 2" TRANSFER HOSE IS MADE OF POLYPROPYLENE AND IT BROKE AT THE POINT WHERE IT CONNECTS TO THE RAILCAR, RESULTING IN A DISHCARGE OF APPROXIMATELY 125 GALLONS ON TO THE GROUND.  THE PRODUCT WAS COLLECTED, NEUTRALIZED AND PUMPED INTO OUR SURFACE IMPOUNDMENT AREA.  WE FEEL THE FITTINGS PROBABLE WEAKENED AND BECAME BRITTLE OVER TIME CAUSING IT TO BREAK.  WE WILL REPLACE OUR RAILCAR POLYPROPYLENE HOSE FITTINGS WITH STAINLESS STEEL FITTINGS WHICH SOULD ELIMINATE THE POSSIBLITY OF THIS HAPPENING AGAIN.

SPILLAGE DUE TO AN INLINE FILTER GASKET LEAK OCCURED WHILE OUR DRIVERS WERE TRANSFERRING WASTE FLAMMABLE LIQUID FROM A RAILWAY TANK CAR TO OUR 6000 GALLON STAINLESS STEEL VACUUM CARGO TANK. WHEN LEAK WAS OBSERVED BY THE DRIVERS, THE LOADING WAS STOPPED IMMEDIATELY, A NEW GASKET WAS INSTALLED IN THE FILTER CAP AND DRIVERS COMPLETED LOADING WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT. THE SPILLED MATERIAL AND CONTAMINATED SOIL WERE COLLECTED IN ONE (1) 85 GALLON OVERPACK DRUM, ONE (1) 17H-55 GALLON DRUM AND BOTH CONTAINERS REMAINED AT THE LOADING SITE WITH THE GENERATOR. PROCEDURES HAVE BEEN INITIATED REQUIRING DRIVERS TO COMPLETE MORE THOROUGH PRE-INSPECTIONS OF ALL CONNECTIONS AND GASKETS PRIOR TO LOADING OR UNLOADING.

column168: DRIVER WAS OFF-LOADING PRODUCT INTO CUSTOMER STORAGE TANK THROUGH THE USE OF COMPRESSED AIR TO THE CARGO TANK.  DURING THE OFF-LOADING, A LEAK DEVELOPED AT THE CONNECTION BETWEEN A TRANSFER HOSE AND THE STROAGE TANK. APPROXIMATELY 30 GALLONS LEAKED TOTHE GROUND BEFORE THE SITUATION COULD BE CORRECTED.  SPILLED PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED IN THE IMMEDIATE AREA AND SUBSEQUENTLY CLEANED UP FOR PROPER DISPOSAL BY PLANT PERSONNEL. INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT A BUILD OF ICE ON THE TRANSFER HOSE INITIALLY MADE IT APPEAR THE CONNECTION WAS TIGHT.  AFTER A SHORT TIME, HOWEVER, THE ICE MELTED/VIBRATED OFF RESULTING IN A LOOSE CONNECTION AND THE LEAK.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: WHILE INSPECTING VEHICLE AT TRUCKSTOP, MONTGOMERY, AL, DRIVER NOTICIED 1 OF 4 55 GALLON DRUMS LEAKING.  DRUM HAD LEAKED ABOUT 1/2 OF ITS CONTENTS. ABSORBANT MATERIAL WAS PLACED ON THE MATERIAL.  A RESPONSE TEAM WAS NOTIFIED.  THEY CLEANED THE TRAILER AND OVERPACKED THE LEAKING DRUM.  THE TRAILER WAS EQUIPPED WITH A 6" SECONDARY CONTAINMENT PAN THEREBY PREVENTING ANY RELEASE OF THE MATERIAL ONTO THE GROUND.  THE CAUSE OF THE DRUM FAILURE WAS DUE TO THE DRUM BEING LOADED ONTO A PIECE OF CERAMIC THAT WAS ON THE TRAILER DECK.  THE CERAMIC WORKED A HOLE INTO THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM AS THE TRUCK PROCEEDED DOWN THE ROAD.  ALL ABSORBANT AND CLEAN-UP MATERIAL WAS PLACED IN OVERPACK DRUMS.  NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER WAS NOTIFIED, REPORT NO. 12050.  THE ALABAMA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT WAS ALSO NOTIFIED.  TRUCK PROCEEDED ON TO FINAL DESTINATION WITHOUT FURHTER INCIDENT.

column168: THE MAINE CENTRAL RAILROAD FACILITY THAT WAS MAETIONED ABOVE USES ABOVE GROUND STORAGE TANKS WHICH REQUIRE A PUMP TO UNLOAD THE DELIVERY TRUCK. PUMPING HAD BEEN GOING ON FOR APPROXIMATELY 25 MINUTES WHEN THE HOSE VIBRATED OFF THE DISCHARGE SIDE OF THE PUMP.  THE VEHICLE PUMP WAS SHUT OFF IMMEDIATELY AND THE STROAGE TANK VALVE WAS ALSO CLOSED.  BY THIS TIME, APPROXIMATELY 40 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL HAD SPILLED ONTO THE GROUND.  THE FOREMAN AT THE RAILROAD WAS NOTIFIED IMMEDIATELY AND ABSORBENT PADS WERE USED TO SOAK UP A PORTION OF THE FUEL.  MANAGEMENT WAS NOTIFIED BACK AT THE MOBIL TERMINAL AND THE DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION NOTIFIED.  THE FOLLOWING MORNING, THERE WERE SEVERAL INCHES OF TOPSOIL REMOVED AND DISPOSED OF BY THE CITY OF WATERVILLE.  TO PREVENT A SIMILAR INCIDENT IN THE FUTURE A CHECK VALVE WAS INSERTED INTO THE UNLOADING FACILITY AT THE RAILROAD AND THE EARS THAT CONNECT THE UNLOADING HOSE TO THE PUMP WILL BE SECURED WITH A WIRE STRAP DURING PUMPING.  THIS WILL PREVENT THE FITTINGS FROM VIBRATING LOOSE.

column168: THIS INCIDENT WAS THE OVERFILLING OF AN UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK (UST). WHEN OUR DRIVER ARRIVED AT ST. MARY'S HOSPITAL, HE WAS MET BY THE HOSPITAL'S BOILER ROOM SUPERVISOR, MR. KEVIN MCNAMARA. MR. MCNAMARA TOLD OUR DRIVER THAT THE TANK HE WAS DELIVERING TO WAS A 20,000 GALLON TANK AND THAT THE GAUGE SAID THAT IT HAD +11,047 GALLONS IN IT PRIOR TO OUR DELIVERY.  OUR DRIVER HAD BROUGHT 7500 GALLONS AS ORDERED BY ST. MARY'S. THIS SHOULD HAVE LEFT HIM WITH WELL OVER 1000 GALLOONS OF ROOM IN THE TANK AFTER DELIVERY.  OUR DRIVER THEN PROCEEDED TOHOOK UP & PUMP OFF HIS LOAD. WHEN HE HAD UNLOADED +6300 GALLONS, THE FUEL CAME OUT THE UST'S VENT PIPE & FLOWED DOWNHILL ONTO THE PARKING LOT WHERE IT WAS CONTAINED. INVESTIGATION INTO THE CAUSE OF THE TANK OVERFILL REVEALED THAT THE HOSPITAL BOILER ROOM SUPERVISOR HAD USED THE WRONG CHART FOR THE GAUGE. THE UST ACTUALLY HAD ALMOST 14,000 GALLONS IN IT PRIOR TO DELIVERY.  NEW YORK STATE DEPT. OF ENVIRONMENTAL CONSERVATION WAS NOTIFIED AND SUPERVISED THE CLEAN-UP, AND ASSIGNED A REFERENCE #8911945 TO THE INCIDENTS.  IN REFERENCE TO SECTIONS VII & VIII ABOVE, I FILLED THESE SECTIONS OUT AS ACCURATELY AS POSSIBLE AS THERE WAS NO ACTUAL "FAILURE" OF ANY OF THE DEVICES INVOLVED IN THE DELIVERY.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 03:11 HRS OF MARCH 15, 1990, I KAREN NICHOLS, (HAZ-MAT COORDIANTOR) AND DON FLOREA (HAZ-MAT SPECIALIST) RESPONDED TO A CAL AT DOOR C-8 OF OUR SORT FACILITY.  JAN CLEAVER (SORT-SUPERVISOR) WHO REPORTED THE SPILL DIRECTED ME TO A "C" CONTAINER WHICH WAS LEAKING A CLEAR LIQUID. MR. FLOREA AND I USED LITMUS PAPER AND GOT A READING OF 12 ON THE COLOR SCALE.   E THEN NOTIFIED AIRBORNE'S SECURITY TO COME TO THAT LOCATION AND SECURE THE AREA.  MR. FLOREA AND THE I THEN BEGAN UNLOADING THE "C" CONTAINER TO FINE THE LEAKING SHIPMENT.  THERE WERE ONLY APPROXIMATELY SIX PIECES OF FRT CONTAMINATED SO WE HELD THOSE TO BE NEUTRALIZED.  WE THEN CONTAINED THE LEAKING SHPT IN A DOT APPROVED RECOVERY DRUM AND NEUTRALIZED THE ENTIRE SPILL OF APPROXIMATELY THREE QUARTS.  THE  SHPT CONTAINED 2 ONE GALLON PLASTIC JUGS OF COMPUND CLEANING LIQUID.  THERE WAS NO INDICATION ON THE OUTER PACKAGING THAT THIS SHPT CONTAINED A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  TH ESHPT IS BEING HELD UNDER LOCK AND KEY TO BE RELEASED BY THE FAA, AT WHICH TIME THE SHPT WILL BE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER IN A DOT APPROVED RECOVERY DRUM.

ON MARCH 24, 1990, AT APPROXIMATELY 04:01 HRS. I, KAREN NICHOLS, HAZ-MAT COORDINATOR AND DON FLOREA, HAZ-MAT SPECIALIST RESPONDED TO A CALL AT DOOR A-24A OF OUR SORT FACILITY. THE FIBERBOEARD BOX APPEARED TO BE LEAKING SO WE IMMEDIATELY PLACED IT IN A PLASTIC BAG.  UPON OPENING THE FIBERBOARD BOX WE NOTICED A HYDROCARBON ODOR, SO WE IMMEDIATELY CLOSED THE BAG TO INVESTIGATE IT IN A WELL VENTED AREA.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION WE FOUND THE FIBERBOARD BOX TO CONTAIN 6 ONE PT GLASS BOTTLES.  ONE OF THE BOTTLES WAS SHATTERED.  RAGS WERE USED AS ABSORBANT.  THE SHIPMENT WAS DOUBLE BAGGED AND PLACED IN OUR ILN HAZ-MAT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY.  IT WILL BE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER IN A DOT APPROVED RECOVERY DRUM.  THERE WAS NO INDICATION ON THE OUTER PKG THAT THE SHPT CONTAINED A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.

column168: 03:25 - JOEL BOTTS REPORTED A POSSIBLE CORROSIVE SPILL AT ONE OF THE FALCON PLANES. 03:28 - CERT 10 (SHAWN HENRY) AND CERT 13 (JEFF HOSTETLER) ARRIVE PLANESIDE 03:29 - SHPT IS FOUND BROKEN OPEN ON THE RAMP APPROXIMATELY FOUR FEET FROM FALCON AIRCRAFT. HAMPER USED TO TRANSPORT SHPT WAS SITTING BESIDE PKG. 03:30 - CERT 10 QUESTIONED P/T SORTER ABOUT SHPT. SORTER ADVISED OF THE FOLLOWING: SHIPMENT WAS BROUGHT PLANESIDE IN THE HAMPER, LEAKAGE WAS DISCOVERED BEFORE SHPT WAS PLACED ON AIRCRAFT, ONE SORTER CAME IN CONTACT. 03:35 - CERT 10 QUESTIONED SCOTT WALLS, P/T SORTER WHO CAME IN CONTACT WITH LEAKAGE FROM SHPT. HE ADVISED THAT ALTHOUGH HE WAS WEARING GLOVES HIS HANDS WERE ITCHING. CERT 10 ASKED IF HE HAD WASHED HIS HANDS, HE STATED NO. CERT 10 ADVISED HIM TO GO FLUSH AFFECTED AREA FOR 10 TO 15 MINUTES. 03:38 - CERT 10 REQUESTED HAZ-MAT BASE TO CALL CFR AND ADVISE THEM OF EMPLOYEE INVOLVED IN SPILL. 03:38 - CERT 10 AND CERT 13 DONNED MASKS, SAFETY GLASSES, AND RUBBER CHEMICAL GLOVES. 03:40 - CERT 10 AND CERT 13 BEGAN FURTHER INSPECTION OF SHPT. 03:42 - SHPT WAS FOUND TO CONTAIN 2 BATERRIES ALONG WITH PLASTIC CONTAINERS FILLED WITH A PINK COLORED LIQUID. 03:45 - CERT 10 AND CERT 13 ATTEMPTED TO PLACE SHPT IN A RECOVERY DRUM, THIS WAS FOUND TO BE TO SMALL TO HOLD ENTIRE SHPT. THE SHPT WAS DOUBLE BAGGED IN SMALL CLEAR BAGS, IT WAS THEN PLACED IN A LARGE HEAVY WHITE BAG. 03:48 - AFFECTED AREAS ON THE RAMP WERE NEUTRALIZED BY CERT 13. 03:51 - CFR ARRIVED ON SCENE TO CHECK P/T SORTER SCOTT WALLS. 03:52 - CERT 10 ADVISED HAZ-MAT BASE THAT EQUIPMENT WAS BEING PUT AWAY. ALSO ADVISED THAT HAMPER AFFECTED FROM THE SPILL WOULD BE ISOLATED UNTILL AFTER THE OPERATION TO BE NEUTRALIZED. 03:53 - CERT 10 ADVISED JOEL BOTTS OF THE ISOLATED HAMPER LOCATED IN THE CUSTOMS CAGE. 03:56 - HAZ-MAT CLEAR OF SPILL. 04:36 - CERT 10 AND CERT 13 RETURN TO CUSTOMS CAGE TO NEUTRALIZE AFFECTED HAMPER. 04:42 - HAZ-MAT CLEAR OF CUSTOMS CAGE. WAS BATTERIES LEAKING ACID. THERE WERE NO MARKINGS ON THE OUTER PKG. THIS SHPT IS BEING HELD UNDER LOCK AND KEY IN THE ILN HAZ-MAT SECURITY CAGE FOR FURTHER FAA INVESTIGATION.

ON 03/21/90 AT APPROXIMATELY 01:42 HRS. A LEAKING SHIPMENT WAS REPORTED TO ME, SHAWN HENRY HAZ-MAT COORDINATOR, AIRBORNE EXPRESS WILMINGTON, OHIO. THIS SHIPMENT WAS LOCATED ON A SLIDE IN THE SORT CENTER.  UPON REACHING THE SLIDE A PART TIME SORTER ADVISED THAT THE LEAKING SHIPMENT LEAKED UPON THE SLIDE ANT THAT THE LIQUID THEN DISSIPATED.   INITIAL INSPECTION OF SHIPMENT INDICATED NO SIGNS OF LEAKAGE.  UPON OPENING FIBERBOARD BOX IT WAS THE CONTENTS RELEASED. ELEVEN OF THE CANS WERE STILL BULL AND SHOWED NO SIGN OF DAMAGE.  THE OUTER FIBERBOARD BOX SHOWED NO INDICATION OF CONTENTS BEING A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  THE INNER TWELVE CANS WERE ALL MARKED "DICHLORODIFLUOROMETHANE".  ACOORDING TO 49 CFR 172.101 DICHLOROFLUOROMETHANE IS CLASSIFIED AS A NON-FLAMMABLE GAS WHICH IS A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  THIS SHIPMENT IS BEING HELD UNDER LOCK AND KEY IN THE ILN HAZ-MAT SECURITY CAGE FOR FAA INVESTIGATION.

column168: ON 03-14-90 AT APPROXIMATELY 0311 HRS. A LEAKING SHIPMENT WAS REPORTED TO ME, SHAWN HENRY HAZ-MAT COORDINATOR, AIRBORNE EXPRESS WILMINGTON, OHIO. THIS SHIPMENT WAS LOCATED ON A SLIDE IN THE SORT CENTER. UPON APPROACHING THE SLIDE INITIAL INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT A FIBERBOARD BOX WAS LEAKING A SMALL AMOUNT OF CLEAR LIQUID. UPON OPENING THE FIBERBOARD BOX THE INNER CONTAINER WAS FOUND TO BE A STYROFOAM BOX. UPON OPENING THE STYROFOAM BOX IT WAS FOUND TO CONTAIN SEVERAL PLASTIC JARS CONTAINING THE CLEAR LIQUID. THE LIQUID HAD AN ODOR SUSPECTED TO BE FORMALDEHYDE, BECAUSE OF THIS A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS REQUESTED. THE MSDS INDICATED THAT THE LIQUID WAS FORMALDEHYDE SOLUTION. UNDER 49 CFR FORMALDEHYDE SOLUTION IS CONSIDERED A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CLASSIFIED AS AN ORM-A. THIS SHIPMENT WAS HELD UNDER LOCK AND KEY IN THE WILMINGTON HAZ-MAT SECURITY CAGE FOR FAA INVESTIGATION.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: AT 02:24 HRS, DON LANGENFELD REPORTED A SPILL IN THE BELLY OF OF AIRCRAFT 805AX.  HAZMAT TEAM CERT 7 (KAREN NICHOLS) AND CERT 6 (DON FLOREA) ARRIVED AT GATE 3 AT 02:29.  UPON APPROACHING THE BELLY, CERT 6 ADVISED ME THAT HE NOTICED AN ODOR OF BATTERY ACID EMMITTING FROM THE BELLY.  THERE WAS PRPOXIMATELY 8 OUNCES OF LIQUID VISIBLE FROM FIRST INSPECTION.  I TOOK A PH READING WITH LITMUS PAPER AND GOT A READING OF O WHICH INDICATES A STRONG ACID.  I IMMEDIATELY ADVISED HAZ-MAT DISPATCH THAT WE WOULD BE TIED UP FOR SEVERAL MINUTES SINCE WE DID HAVE AN ACID.  HAZ-MAT DISPATCH REQUESTED CFR FOR BACKUP AT 02:40.  AT 02:41 CFR WAS ON SCENE.  CERT 7 WAS ADVISED BY CERT 2 (JIM CURTIS) THAT SPLASH SUITS NEED TO BE WORN.  I ADVISED HIM THAT AFTER FURTHER VISUAL INSPECTIONS, SPLAHS SUITS WOULD BE WORN.  AT 02:33, CHRIS PRICE REPORTED AN ODOR TOPSIDE OF TH SAM AIRCRAFT. AT 02:40 8 WENT TOPSIDE TO INVESTIGAE THE ODOR.  I FOUND A LONG STREAM OF LIQUID THAT GAVE THE SAME PH RADING AS WHAT THE SPILL IN THE BELLY DID "PH-O, A STRONG ACID" (FIRE 3 BRUCE CUNNINGHAM) JOINED ME TOPSIDE.  WE DECIDED THAT THE SPILL DEFINITELY HAD TO HAVE BEEN LEAKING FROM A C CONTAINER, PROBABLY ONE LOADED IN THE REAR OF THE AIRCRAFT.  I WENT BACK TO THE BELLY TO ADVISE CERT 6 AND FIRE 6 (JOHN JOHNSON), WHO WERE ALREADY DONNING SPLASH SUITS  AND CARTRIDGE MASKS, TO COME TOPSIDE TO UNLOAD THE REMAINING CONTAINERS.  JIM TAYLOR AND ANTHONY GEORGE WERE PRESENT AND WERE KEPT UPDATED FIRST HAND OF ALL PROCEDURES.  AFTER TOPSIDE WAS CLEAR OF FREIGHT, I INSTRUCTED FIRE 3 TO GO AHEAD AND NEUTRALIZED ALL THAT WAS ACCESSIBLE TOPSIDE.  AT THE SAME TIME, FIRE 6 AND CERT 6 UNLOADED THE EXPERSS PACKS FROM BELLY 4, THEN THEY UNLOADED THE UNAFFECTED FREIGHT FROM BELLY 3.  AT APPRXIMATELY 03:45 HRS, HAZ-MAT BASE CONTACTED MAINTENANCE CONTROL THAT THERE WAS AN ACID WHICH LEAKED THRU THE FLOOR OF THE AIRCRAFT AND THEY WOULD HAVE TO REMOVE THE FLOOR PANELS TO SEE IF THE AIRCRAFT WOULD HAVE TO BE GROUNDED.  AT 03:16, THE LEAKING SHPT WAS DISCOVERED IN THE C BUILDING FEED BY A SORTER.  PHIL SPAHR CALLLED HAZ-MAT DISPATCH.  AT 03"20 CERT TEAM CERT 10 (SHAWN HENRY) AND CERT 13 (JEFF HOSTELTLER) WERE ON SCENE.  UPON OPENING THE CONTIANER, THEY FOUND A FIBREBOARD BOX LEAKING ONTO 3 OTHER PCS OF FREIGHT.  CERT 10 TOOK A PH READING AND IT READ O, ACID.  THE SAME AS WHAT WE HAD AT THE AIRCRAFT.  THE OUTER BOX SAID "TRAILOR SHINE".  HTERE WERE NO MARKINGS INDICATING CORROSIVE ON THE OUTER BOX.  WEARING CHEMICAL GLOVES AND SAFETY GLASSES, CERT 10 AND CERT 13 OPENED THE BOX AND FOUND A WHITE 5 GALLON PLASTIC PAIL LEAKING.  THE TOP CLOSURE WAS LOOSE AND THE PAIL WAS NEAR EMPTY. CERT 10 ADVISED HAZ-MAT BASE OF HER FINDINGS AND WERE CLEAR OF THE SCENE AT 03:26 AFTER ISOLATING THE CONTAINER, (NOTE-PHOTOES WERE TAKEN AFTER OPS AND AFTER THE CONTAINER WAS OPENED.  THE SHPT WAS REPLACED IN THE POSITION IT WAS FOUND.  THESE PHOTOS SHOW MORE DAMAGE THEN WHAT WAS FOUND BY CERT 10.)  HAZ-MAT BASE NOTIFIED ME OF THE COMMODITY FOU

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: VEHICLE #280353, DRIVEN BY FED EX. PLOYEE BILL GREER, WAS HEADED EAST ON ROUTE 76 HWEN STOPPED BY OFFICER WARD OF THE PENNSYLVANIS STATE POLICE.  A LIQUID WAS DRIPPING FROM THE REAR OF THE FORD DELIVERY VAN, FURTHER INSPECTION REVEALED THE MATERIAL TO BE INK.  LEAKAGE WAS DUE TO DAMAGE TO THE DRUM BY OTHER FREIGHT IN THE VAN AND THE CRIP-ON LID WAS NOT PROPERLY SECURED AS IT COULD BE ROTATED FREELY WHILE STILL ATTACHED TO THE DRUM. THE FREIGHT IN THE VAN WAS NOT SECURED, AND FELL ONTO THE ROADWAY WHEN THE DOOR WAS OPENED.  THE STEEL DRUM HAD OVERTURNED, AND IN CONJUCTION WITH THE LOOSE TOP, ALL THEINK HAD LEAKED OUT INTO THE VAN, AND WAS LEAKING FROM UNDER THE DOOR DURING TRANSIT.  THE DRIVER WAS FINED $200.00 FOR VIOLATION OF VEHICLE CODE 49.3; THE MATERIAL ON THE ROADWAY WAS REMOVED BY FED EX PERSONNEL.  THE ENTIRE SHIPMENT OF 7 DRUMS, INCLUDING THE ONE WHICH LEAKED AND WAS NOW EMPTY, WERE PICKED UP BY THE SHIPPER.  CORRECTIVE MEASURES HAVE BEEN IMPLEMENTED TO PREVENT ANY SIMILAR INCIDENT IN THE FUTURE.  THESE MEASURES INCLUDE 'BUNGEE CORDS' FOR PROPER SECURING OF THE FREIGHT AND 3 SEPARATE INSPECTIONS OF THE FINAL LOAD PRIOR TO DEPARTURE OF THE VANS.

TERMINAL MANAGER, T.W. BASS REPORTED TANK CAR SLOSHING FROM THE TOP WHEN CAR WAS MOVED. CAR ISOLATED. SHIPPER NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC. SHIPPER HAD RESCAR RESPOND ON 3/9/90 AND REPLACE A BLOWN RUPTURE DISC.

ON ARRIVAL FLT 226/04 MARCH (1425 HRS) (ACFT #9013), WHEN FWD BIN WAS OPENED TO REMOVE BAGS THE FLOOR JUST INSIDE WAS WET WITH BATTERY ACID WHICH HAD LEAKED FROM BATTERY-OPERATED WHEELCHAIR ACCOMPANYING PASSENGERS (FRED & JAN EGGERT) AS CHECKED BAGGAGE TO TPA.  RSM NEUTRALIZED WITH CLUB SODA AND MOPPED DRY.  MCI MTNCE WAS CONTACTED TO REPORT INCIDENT AND INSTRUCTED US TO HAVE NW (ON-CALL MTNCE) INSPECT/PULL FLOOR PANNEL AND CHECKED FOR SEEPAGE.  2 PANNELS WERE REMOVED AND MINIMAL SEEPAGE HAD OCCURRED, HOWEVER NONT HAD REACHED ACFT SKIN.  TRACE OF SEEPAGE ON FOIL INSULATION WAS REMOVED & PANELS REPLACED & LOG BOOK NOTED WITH MCI MTNCE APPROVAL FOR OPERATION OF OUTBOUND FLIGHT 55/04 MARCH *(WHICH SUSTAINED A 43 MIN. CODE 19 DELAY CHARGE TO STL PER MCI MTNCE).  THE INBOUND INCIDENT WAS USED AS AN EXAMPLE FOR TRAINING AND CORRECTIVE ACTION TAKEN ON PASSENGERS RETURN TO MSP *(75/18MAR TPA STL 693/18MAR STL MSP).  BATTERIES REMOVED AND PLACED IN APPROVED SHIPPING CARTONS, PROPERLY LABELED AND MARKED, AND COMPLETION OF FORM F-917 MADE AND GIVEN TO PILOT IN COMMAND. NO DAMAGE OR INJURY TO PASSENGERS.  PRECAUTIONARY INSPECTION & CLEANUP ON ACFT.
